        "title" : "Introduction to PGQL constructs",
        "hasTitle" : true,
        "message" : [
          "%md",
          "## Intro to PGQL constructs by example",
          "This notebook shows example of using various PGQL constructs on the sales history (**SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH**) graph created from the SH schema.",
          "The PGQL specification and examples are available at: [https://pgql-lang.org/](https://pgql-lang.org/)",
          "",
          "### Prerequisite",
          "- The **SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH graph should have been created and loaded into memory**.  ",
          "  Do that from either  ",
          "  - the <a href=\"/graphstudio/#/gs-graphs\" target=\"_blank\">Graphs</a> page if the graph has been created (Rt-click on the row for the SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH graph and then select Load into Memory).",
          "  - or go through the steps in the sample notebook <a href=\"/graphstudio/#/workspace/Use%20Cases\" target=\"_blank\">under Use Cases</a>. That notebook lists the steps required to create and load the graph.",
          "",
          "The Graphs page also gives you details on the Vertices and Edges, i.e. their Labels and Properties"
        ],
        "selectedVisualization" : "html",
        "visualizationConfig" : null,
        "hideCode" : true,
        "hideResult" : false,
        "hideGutter" : false,
        "hideVizConfig" : false,
        "hideInIFrame" : false,
        "enabled" : true,
        "forms" : "[]",
        "result" : {
          "startTime" : 1661354808250,
          "endTime" : 1661354808333,
          "interpreter" : "md",
          "taskStatus" : "SUCCESS",
          "status" : "SUCCESS",
          "results" : [
            {
              "message" : "<h2 id=\"intro-to-pgql-constructs-by-example\">Intro to PGQL constructs by example</h2>\n<p>This notebook shows example of using various PGQL constructs on the sales history (<strong>SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH</strong>) graph created from the SH schema.\nThe PGQL specification and examples are available at: <a href=\"https://pgql-lang.org/\">https://pgql-lang.org/</a></p>\n<h3 id=\"prerequisite\">Prerequisite</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH graph should have been created and loaded into memory</strong>.<br />\nDo that from either\n<ul>\n<li>the <a href=\"/graphstudio/#/gs-graphs\" target=\"_blank\">Graphs</a> page if the graph has been created (Rt-click on the row for the SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH graph and then select Load into Memory).</li>\n<li>or go through the steps in the sample notebook <a href=\"/graphstudio/#/workspace/Use%20Cases\" target=\"_blank\">under Use Cases</a>. That notebook lists the steps required to create and load the graph.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Graphs page also gives you details on the Vertices and Edges, i.e. their Labels and Properties</p>\n",
              "type" : "HTML"
            }
          ],
          "forms" : null
        },
        "relations" : [ ],
        "dynamicFormParams" : "{}"
      },
      {
        "row" : 0,
        "col" : 0,
        "sizeX" : 0,
        "width" : 12,
        "title" : null,
        "hasTitle" : false,
        "message" : [
          "%md",
          "The Graphs page tells you the number of vertices, e.g. 976772, and edges, e.g. 4649715. ",
          "It does not, however, tell how many types of vertices and edges there are. That is, what are their labels.",
          "So let's do that.",
          "",
          "### Query 1: Find the Vertex labels. ",
          "We use the built-in `label()` function here. `MATCH (v)` specifies the graph pattern with matches any vertex. `DISTINCT` eliminates duplicates  ",
          "`SELECT DISTINCT LABEL(v) as Vertex_Label FROM MATCH (v) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH` ",
          "",
          "### Query 2: Find the Edge labels",
          "`MATCH ()-[e]->()` matches any directed edge e.  ",
          "`SELECT DISTINCT LABEL(e) as Edge_Label FROM MATCH ()-[e]->() on SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH` "
        ],
        "selectedVisualization" : "html",
        "visualizationConfig" : null,
        "hideCode" : true,
        "hideResult" : false,
        "hideGutter" : true,
        "hideVizConfig" : false,
        "hideInIFrame" : false,
        "enabled" : true,
        "forms" : "[]",
        "result" : {
          "startTime" : 1661354893963,
          "endTime" : 1661354894071,
          "interpreter" : "md",
          "taskStatus" : "SUCCESS",
          "status" : "SUCCESS",
          "results" : [
            {
              "message" : "<p>The Graphs page tells you the number of vertices, e.g. 976772, and edges, e.g. 4649715.\nIt does not, however, tell how many types of vertices and edges there are. That is, what are their labels.\nSo let's do that.</p>\n<h3 id=\"query-1-find-the-vertex-labels\">Query 1: Find the Vertex labels.</h3>\n<p>We use the built-in <code>label()</code> function here. <code>MATCH (v)</code> specifies the graph pattern with matches any vertex. <code>DISTINCT</code> eliminates duplicates<br />\n<code>SELECT DISTINCT LABEL(v) as Vertex_Label FROM MATCH (v) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH</code></p>\n<h3 id=\"query-2-find-the-edge-labels\">Query 2: Find the Edge labels</h3>\n<p><code>MATCH ()-[e]-&gt;()</code> matches any directed edge e.<br />\n<code>SELECT DISTINCT LABEL(e) as Edge_Label FROM MATCH ()-[e]-&gt;() on SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH</code></p>\n",
              "type" : "HTML"
            }
          ],
          "forms" : null
        },
        "relations" : [ ],
        "dynamicFormParams" : "{}"
