        "hasTitle" : false,
        "message" : [
          "%md",
          "The basic structure of a PGQL query is **SELECT** some entities **FROM MATCH** a graph pattern **ON** some graph **WHERE** some condition holds.",
          "So let's add a WHERE clause and find how many Sales there were in the calendar year 1998.",
          "",
          "We can look at the vertex and edge properties (i.e. the metadata) on the Graphs page. From there we know the edge labeled `DATE_OF_SALE` links Sales to dates ",
          "(i.e. the TIMES vertex) and TIMES has a property named `CALENDAR_YEAR`",
          "",
          "Here we'll use two other PGQL constructs. One to reference a property (e.g. `v.CALENDAR_YEAR`) and one to specify an edge or vertex **label predicate**, ",
          "e.g. `v:SALES` or `e:DATE_OF_SALE`  to limit the search by those labels.",
          "",
          "The FROM clause can contain multiple MATCH clauses. ",
          "",
          "We can use that to find the number of sales in 1998 by channel. We can use to match clauses, one for sales by year and the other for sales by channel, or combine them as one pattern.",
          "",
          "**Note**: In query 6 and 7 a **repeated variable** such as `s` refers to the same vertex. ",
          "",
          "### Query 5: how many Sales occurred in the calendar year 1998",
          "`SELECT COUNT(v) as Number_Of_Sales FROM MATCH (s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]->(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998`",
          "",
          "### Query 6: How many sales occurred through each channel in the calendar year 1998",
          "`SELECT c.CHANNEL_DESC as Channel_Desc, count(s) as NumSales FROM MATCH (s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]->(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH, MATCH (s:SALES)-[e2:SALES_CHANNELS]->(c) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH ",
          " WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY Channel_Desc`",
          "",
          "### Query 7: Same as above but with a single MATCH pattern",
          "`SELECT c.CHANNEL_DESC as Channel_Desc, count(s) as NumSales FROM MATCH (c)<-[e2:VIA_CHANNEL]-(s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]->(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY Channel_Desc`"
        ],
        "selectedVisualization" : "html",
        "visualizationConfig" : null,
        "hideCode" : true,
        "hideResult" : false,
        "hideGutter" : true,
        "hideVizConfig" : false,
        "hideInIFrame" : false,
        "enabled" : true,
        "forms" : "[]",
        "result" : {
          "startTime" : 1661347823786,
          "endTime" : 1661347823911,
          "interpreter" : "md",
          "taskStatus" : "SUCCESS",
          "status" : "SUCCESS",
          "results" : [
            {
              "message" : "<p>The basic structure of a PGQL query is <strong>SELECT</strong> some entities <strong>FROM MATCH</strong> a graph pattern <strong>ON</strong> some graph <strong>WHERE</strong> some condition holds.\nSo let's add a WHERE clause and find how many Sales there were in the calendar year 1998.</p>\n<p>We can look at the vertex and edge properties (i.e. the metadata) on the Graphs page. From there we know the edge labeled <code>DATE_OF_SALE</code> links Sales to dates\n(i.e. the TIMES vertex) and TIMES has a property named <code>CALENDAR_YEAR</code></p>\n<p>Here we'll use two other PGQL constructs. One to reference a property (e.g. <code>v.CALENDAR_YEAR</code>) and one to specify an edge or vertex <strong>label predicate</strong>,\ne.g. <code>v:SALES</code> or <code>e:DATE_OF_SALE</code>  to limit the search by those labels.</p>\n<p>The FROM clause can contain multiple MATCH clauses.</p>\n<p>We can use that to find the number of sales in 1998 by channel. We can use to match clauses, one for sales by year and the other for sales by channel, or combine them as one pattern.</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: In query 6 and 7 a <strong>repeated variable</strong> such as <code>s</code> refers to the same vertex.</p>\n<h3 id=\"query-5-how-many-sales-occurred-in-the-calendar-year-1998\">Query 5: how many Sales occurred in the calendar year 1998</h3>\n<p><code>SELECT COUNT(v) as Number_Of_Sales FROM MATCH (s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]-&gt;(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998</code></p>\n<h3 id=\"query-6-how-many-sales-occurred-through-each-channel-in-the-calendar-year-1998\">Query 6: How many sales occurred through each channel in the calendar year 1998</h3>\n<p><code>SELECT c.CHANNEL_DESC as Channel_Desc, count(s) as NumSales FROM MATCH (s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]-&gt;(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH, MATCH (s:SALES)-[e2:SALES_CHANNELS]-&gt;(c) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH  WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY Channel_Desc</code></p>\n<h3 id=\"query-7-same-as-above-but-with-a-single-match-pattern\">Query 7: Same as above but with a single MATCH pattern</h3>\n<p><code>SELECT c.CHANNEL_DESC as Channel_Desc, count(s) as NumSales FROM MATCH (c)&lt;-[e2:VIA_CHANNEL]-(s:SALES)-[e:DATE_OF_SALE]-&gt;(t:TIMES) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY Channel_Desc</code></p>\n",
              "type" : "HTML"
            }
          ],
          "forms" : null
        },
