        "width" : 12,
        "title" : null,
        "hasTitle" : false,
        "message" : [
          "%md ",
          "#### Path macros and variable length paths",
          "",
          "The PGQL language specification has more details and examples of the various possibilities. We will use a contrived example here because the paths and path lengths can be expressed more efficiently for thie SH graph without macros and regular expressions.",
          "",
          "#### Query 10: Show number of sales by country for the calendar year 1998",
          "/* Since we know the graph is (time)<-(sales)->(cust)->(country) we could just use that */",
          "",
          "SELECT c.COUNTRY_NAME, count(*) as NumSales FROM MATCH (t)<-(s)->(cust)->(c) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY c.COUNTRY_NAME ORDER BY NumSales DESC",
          "",
          "We can however express that using a path macro too.",
          "",
          "PATH has_path AS (:COUNTRIES)<-(:CUSTOMERS)<-()->()  ",
          "SELECT c.COUNTRY_NAME, count(*) as NumSales FROM MATCH (c)-/:has_path/->(t) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY c.COUNTRY_NAME ORDER BY NumSales ASC",
          "",
          "Note: We know (:COUNTRIES)<-(:CUSTOMERS)<-()->() can match only once we can omit the + (which indicates 1 or more matches). i.e. /:has_path/ == /:has_path{1,1}/"
        ],
        "selectedVisualization" : "html",
        "visualizationConfig" : null,
        "hideCode" : true,
        "hideResult" : false,
        "hideGutter" : true,
        "hideVizConfig" : false,
        "hideInIFrame" : false,
        "enabled" : true,
        "forms" : "[]",
        "result" : {
          "startTime" : 1661348867346,
          "endTime" : 1661348867473,
          "interpreter" : "md",
          "taskStatus" : "SUCCESS",
          "status" : "SUCCESS",
          "results" : [
            {
              "message" : "<h4 id=\"path-macros-and-variable-length-paths\">Path macros and variable length paths</h4>\n<p>The PGQL language specification has more details and examples of the various possibilities. We will use a contrived example here because the paths and path lengths can be expressed more efficiently for thie SH graph without macros and regular expressions.</p>\n<h4 id=\"query-10-show-number-of-sales-by-country-for-the-calendar-year-1998\">Query 10: Show number of sales by country for the calendar year 1998</h4>\n<p>/* Since we know the graph is (time)&lt;-(sales)-&gt;(cust)-&gt;(country) we could just use that */</p>\n<p>SELECT c.COUNTRY_NAME, count(*) as NumSales FROM MATCH (t)&lt;-(s)-&gt;(cust)-&gt;(c) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY c.COUNTRY_NAME ORDER BY NumSales DESC</p>\n<p>We can however express that using a path macro too.</p>\n<p>PATH has_path AS (:COUNTRIES)&lt;-(:CUSTOMERS)&lt;-()-&gt;()<br />\nSELECT c.COUNTRY_NAME, count(*) as NumSales FROM MATCH (c)-/:has_path/-&gt;(t) ON SH_PGVIEW_GRAPH WHERE t.CALENDAR_YEAR=1998 GROUP BY c.COUNTRY_NAME ORDER BY NumSales ASC</p>\n<p>Note: We know (:COUNTRIES)&lt;-(:CUSTOMERS)&lt;-()-&gt;() can match only once we can omit the + (which indicates 1 or more matches). i.e. /:has_path/ == /:has_path{1,1}/</p>\n",
              "type" : "HTML"
            }
          ],
          "forms" : null
        },
